Justice Olukayode Ariwoola is from Iseyin in Iseyin Local Government Area of Oyo State. He was born on August 22, 1954 and is expected to retire from the Supreme Court on August 22, 2024. Justice Ariwoola started his education at the Local Authority Demonstration School, Oluwole, in Iseyin Local Government of Oyo State between 1959 and 1967. He attended the Muslim Modern School in the same town between 1968 and 1969 before moving to the Ansar-Ud-Deen High School, Saki, in Oyo North of Oyo State. Justice Ariwoola studied law at the University of Ife (now Obafemi Awolowo University), lle Ife and graduated in July 1980. He was called to the bar in July 1981 after leaving the Nigerian Law School. He was sworn in as a judge of the High Court of Oyo State on November 2, 1992, after some years in private legal practice. On November 22, 2005, he was sworn in as a Justice of the Court of Appeal. Justice Ariwoola was inaugurated on November 22, 2011, as a Justice of the Supreme Court.   Herders kill man for knocking down cow in Badagry     Bridging skill gaps in plumbing     5G: Nigeria begins race for 4.4b global subscriptions   Justice Ariwoola is not known to be controversial. He headed the seven-member panel of the Supreme Court that reversed the decision by the Lagos State Government to regulate the use of head covering (hijab) by female Muslim students in public schools in the state. Justice Ariwoola was one of the five Muslims on the panel, who gave the majority decision. The two Christian members disagreed. Another Muslim, Justice Kudirat Kekere-Ekun (from Lagos State), wrote the lead majority judgment delivered on June 17, 2022, in the appeal marked: SC/910/2016 filed by the Lagos State Government. Other Muslims in the panel were Justices Uwani Abba-Aji, Mohammed Lawal Garba and Tijani Abubakar Justice Emmanuel Agim wrote the lead minority decision, with which Justice Inyang Okoro agreed. The judgment has continued to generate reactions, with a lawyer, Malcom Omirhobo, dressing to the Supreme Court on June 23, 2022, in strange attire. Omirhobo, who combined his law regalia with that of his traditional religious dress, claimed to be reacting to the judgment. Justice Ariwoola also headed the five-member panel that dismissed the appeal filed by former Transportation Minister Rotimi Amaechi against the decision of Rivers State Governor Nyesom Wike to set up a panel to probe his administration. In the judgment delivered on May 27, 2022, in the appeal marked: SC/911/2017, the Supreme Court held that the appeal was without merit and awarded a N1million cost against Amaechi.